<div itemprop="articleBody">
<h1>Tutorial 42. Adjusting the Corset Pattern with 2 Princess Seams.</h1>
<p><strong>I have drawn the initial corset pattern on the writing board. It needs to be adjusted after client’s measurements by the automatically calculated values from the table. </strong></p>
<p><strong>The first thing I do is remove 0.3cm along the full length of the centre front piece by shifting the fold line inwards. </strong></p>
<p>This adjustment is necessary because my client’s Bust Princess Seam Width is 19cm which is 0.5cm smaller than on the initial pattern.</p>
<p>Naturally enough, a 19cm distance between bust princess seams is the smallest possible distance for a Bust Circumference of 98cm.</p>
<p>The actual distance will be more than 19cm because the cups of a low-neck corset tend to slightly come apart thereby increasing the distance between bust princess seams.</p>
<p>But if you are making a boat-neck corset, a strapless corset, or a corset with some other kind of a modest neck, then a Bust Princess Seam Width of 19cm is way too small for a Bust Circumference of 98cm.</p>
<p>In our particular case with a low V-neck, 19cm is quite a normal distance.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image053.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image054.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>According to the calculations, the front side seam line needs to be shifted 2.8cm outwards. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image055.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I re-draw the front side seam line. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Let me remind you </strong>that you should use the initial pattern as a template to preserve the initial side seam length. <strong>I mark the top and bottom points of the side seam and transfer the notches. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image056.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The back side seam line needs to be shifted 1.5cm outwards. I re-draw it, mark the top and bottom points, and transfer all notches. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image057.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I start adjusting the back princess seam lines.</strong></p>
<p><strong>According to the calculations, I shift it 0.3cm inwards at the bust line level, 0.5cm outwards at the under-bust line level, 0.3cm outwards at the waistline, and 0.4cm at the stomach line. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image058.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I accidentally marked the bust line adjustment at the under-bust line level. As the result, the under-bust line adjustment was also marked incorrectly. These points must be placed higher.</strong></p>
<p><strong>I re-draw the back princess seam lines. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image059.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Let us move to the front princess seam line.</strong> It should also be adjusted.</p>
<p><strong>I shift it 0.3cm outwards at the waistline and 0.4cm inwards at the stomach level. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image060.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I re-draw the front princess seam lines accordingly.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image061.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>And now I would like to take a small break and give you some recommendations. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Our client is a stately woman with a little bit of a stomach </strong>which is shown by the 0.3cm added at the waistline level.</p>
<p>You may get surprised but <strong>I recommend you should not narrow the corset additionally in the stomach but narrow the bust darts between the waistline and the under-bust line to achieve a better fit in the stomach area. </strong>This will allow you to slightly widen the corset there and straighten the princess seam under the bust, which will also improve the neckline fit.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image062.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image063.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>One more thing: never try to improve the cup fit by taking in the front princess seam under the bust! </strong></p>
<p><strong>This will result in too much tension under the cups and they will start gapping. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image064.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Let us move to Clip measurements. </strong></p>
<p><strong>According to the calculations, the clip toward the top of the garment needs to be made 2.3cm longer. </strong></p>
<p><strong>And here I want to pause again to give you some more useful tips. </strong></p>
<p>I emphasize it in many courses by the Corset Academy that you must shorten the bust dart at the top when you lengthen the clip toward the top corner of the corset in large-size garments.</p>
<p>The larger the bust is, the smaller the dart should be.</p>
<p>And this means you cannot just prolong the princess seam line upwards to raise the cup.</p>
<p><strong>This may result in a very strange and unattractive bust shape: </strong>the bust will be squeezed flat at the top and pushed out forward at the bottom.</p>
<p><strong>For this reason, I recommend you should narrow the dart: in our case, literally by 2-3mm. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image065.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Some teachers recommend you slash the side front piece along the bust line, raise the cup by the length added to the clip measurement, outline the removed part of the piece, and re-draw the bust princess seam line. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image066.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I am not a fan of this method </strong>because, judging from my personal experience, it results in a rather large distance between the initial and the new princess seam line. In other words, the under-bust dart becomes a lot narrower, which has a negative impact on the fit of the cups.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image067.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>For those who follow this method of re-drawing the bust princess seam line, I usually recommend they draw a new princess seam line (red dashed line) in about the middle between the initial line and the line they get after outlining the separated top part of the side front piece. </strong></p>
<p><strong>After drawing the new bust princess seam line and adding seam allowances, you can continue working on the top part of the side front piece. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image068.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I continue working with Clip measurements. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Clip toward Armscye needs to be made 2.5cm longer as follows from the calculations. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image069.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image070.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Attention! We have approached one of the most crucial moments in our pattern adjustment process. </strong></p>
<p><strong>You can see it from the table that the under-bust dart has a depth of 1.8cm. </strong></p>
<p><strong>This value must be marked from the top point of the front side seam line after you prolong this line. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image071.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>After adding this 1.8cm under-bust dart depth and a seam allowance to the front side seam line, we can re-draw the armscye line of the pattern. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image072.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>The front side seam line became longer by the width of the future dart – 1.8cm.</strong></p>
<p><strong>So now we can safely mark 0.9cm above and below the under-bust line (½ dart width) to achieve a total dart opening of 1.8cm. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image073.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>After we sew the under-bust dart, the length of the front side seam line will match the length of the back side seam line again. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image074.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The two side seam lines will be aligned perfectly and the whole top of the corset will spread out properly. The dart will improve the bust fit. Moreover, 1.1cm of eased-in cup fabric will only make it better regardless of whether they are soft or hard cups.</strong></p>
<p><strong>I add 1cm to the Clip toward Middle of Neckline on the centre front piece and raise its top to match the level of the side front piece. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image075.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>The original garment had a sweetheart neckline so we can make the neckline corners round. </strong>But you should keep it in mind and explain it to your client that the sharp neckline corner will disguise that roll of fat which will inevitably arise after lacing the corset. Of course, you can try to disguise it with the help of the lace top, but leaving these corners sharp is a good option, too. Discuss it with your client.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image076.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>All I need to do with the back is lengthen it by 3cm at the top.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image077.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>In conclusion, let me say something about the lacing. </strong>I would not recommend you trim the centre back pieces at an angle to make the lacing edges form a V or an A on corsets made for full-figured ladies. It will look a lot better with the back halves meeting neatly edge-to-edge. The most I can agree with is when you make the centre back piece just a little narrower so you can lace the corset a little tighter. But you should be very careful here because you will likely get fat rolls along the spine which will look not very good despite the lace top.</p>
<p><strong>As for me, I prefer to lace the back edge-to-edge. You can make any kind of a cut-out above the lacing area and decorate it with buttons or any other décor to your liking. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2042.files/image078.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>We have customized the pattern! </strong></p>

</div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody -->
</div> <!-- Scope END: Article -->
<!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin -->
 
					</div>

					
					
					<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">
						<p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p>
<p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p>
<p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p>
<a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20boat.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Boat-Neck Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20strapless.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> 
Strapless Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20V%20neck.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> 
V-Neck Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/corset%20-%20neck%20strap.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> 
